Daewoo Securities, HSBC, Hyundai, Pintaras: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-09-07T21:49:13Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-07/daewoo-securities-hsbc-pintaras-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Asian trading, excluding  Japan .
Stock symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  Daewoo Securities Co. (006800 KS):  South Korea ’s second-
largest brokerage by market value plans to sell 136.6 million
new shares to raise 1.4 trillion won ($1.3 billion), according
to a regulatory filing. Daewoo Securities advanced 3.8 percent
to 13,750 won.  HSBC Holdings Plc (HSBA)  (5 HK):  Europe ’s largest bank plans to
cut 3,000 jobs in  Hong Kong  over the next three years to reduce
costs and boost profitability. “At HSBC, we recognize the need
to become more efficient and less bureaucratic,” a spokeswoman
who declined to be identified citing company policy, said in a
telephone interview yesterday. HSBC climbed 0.8 percent to
HK$64.60.  Hyundai Motor Co. (005380)  (005380 KS): The company’s Indian unit
will introduce its HA small car this year, Arvind Saxena,
director of sales and marketing, said in an interview in New
Delhi. Hyundai Motor, South Korea’s biggest automaker, gained
3.7 percent to 199,000 won.  Oriental Peninsula Resources Group Inc. (ORE)  : The
Philippine metals producer said it “secured” investments from
Yun Feng, which owns automotive companies and suppliers in  China ,
to invest in its hydropower, coal and nickel projects, a stock-
exchange filing showed. The stock fell 1.3 percent to 4.50 pesos.  Pintaras Jaya Bhd. (PINT)  : The Malaysian construction
group won a 54.9 million-ringgit ($18 million) building contract
from Oasis Garden Development Sdn., according to a company
statement. Pintaras added 5.5 percent to 2.50 ringgit.  Samsung Electronics Co. (005930 KS): The world’s second-
biggest mobile phone maker and  Microsoft Corp. (MSFT)  may team up to
develop tablet computers based on Microsoft’s Windows 8
operating system, the Korea Economic Daily reported, without
citing anyone. Samsung Electronics advanced 6.3 percent to
773,000 won.  United Microelectronics Corp. (2303)  (2303 TT): The world’s
second-largest contract maker of chips bought NT$2.15 billion
($73.8 million) of gear from ASML Hong Kong Ltd. from Aug. 5 to
Sept. 7, UMC said in a statement to the Taiwan stock exchange.
The stock rose 4.6 percent to NT$11.40.  To contact the reporter on this story:
